text: The Total Synthesis of Heraclemycin B through b-Ketosulfoxide and Aldehyde Annulation Kieran D. Jones,[a] James E. Rixson,[a] Brian W. Skelton,[b] Kersten M. Gericke,[c] and Scott G. Stewart*[a] This article is dedicated to Dr. Lindsay Byrne the occasion of his retirement The 4 H-anthra[1,2-b]-pyran-4,7,12-trione secondary metabolites were first described over fifty years ago with the discovery of pluramycin A from an isolate of S. pluricolorescens.[1] These an- thrapyranone class of compounds have been isolated from a variety of bacteria and often display potent biological activi- ty, making them viable targets for synthesis studies. An impres- sive collection of anthrapyranones have been isolated mainly from marine and soil derived Streptomyces sp. bacteria. Along with pluramycin A, some of the most important anthrapyra- nones in the literature include kidamycin and hedamycin; iso- lated from S. phaeoverticillatus[2] and S. grisoruber,[3] respective- ly. Recently a series of previously unreported anthrapyranone and novel anthraquinone natural products 1–4 (Figure 1) have been reported following bioassay guided isolation studies con- ducted on Streptomyces sp. Y3111 found in the stems of the traditional Chinese medicine Heracleum souliei.[4] These novel secondary metabolites have appropriately been named ((cid:156))-heraclemycin A–D (1–4). Accompanying antibacterial stud- ies involving Bacillus Calmette-Guƒrin (BCG), an attenuated strain of Mycobacerium bovis., indicated that ((cid:156))-heraclemy- cin C and D (2 and 4) had the lowest minimum inhibition con- centrations (MIC) of 6.25 mg mL¢1 and 25 mg mL¢1, respectively. Stewart School of Chemistry and Biochemistry The University of Western Australia (M310) 35 Stirling Highway, Crawley WA 6009 (Australia) E-mail: scott.stewart@uwa.edu.au Abstract: Herein we describe a total synthesis of the natural product heraclemycin B. This synthetic approach follows a Diels–Alder strategy to form the anthracenone core fol- Centre for Microscopy, Characterisation and Analysis The University of Western Australia Crawley, WA 6009 (Australia) Bayer Pharma AG Medicinal Chemistry 42096 Wuppertal (Germany) Supporting information for this article is available on the WWW under http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/ajoc.201500184. DOI: 10.1002/ajoc.201500184 lowed by a b-ketosulfoxide and aldehyde annulation to form the 4-pyranone D ring. The spectral data for the synthesized product matches that reported in the isolation studies. Figure 1. Natural products heraclemycins A–D. The heraclemycin natural products were also tested against a larger panel of bacteria. Heraclemycin A and D (1 and 4) showed activity against both Gram-positive bacteria, with MICs of 50 mg mL¢1 and 25 mg mL¢1 respectively, while heraclemy- cin B (3) showed activity (MICs of 50 mg mL¢1) against Staphylo- coccus aureus (ATCC 6538) and a clinical strain of methicillin-re- sistant S. aureus.

In order to further study the specific antibacterial activity of ((cid:156))-heraclemycin A–D (1–4) displayed on Bacillus Calmette- Guƒrin and eventual structure-activity relationship (SAR) stud- ies, we were interested in preparing larger quantities of these natural products. Synthetic approaches to anthrapyranones most commonly involve a late cyclisation of the 4-pyranone D ring. Some of these approaches include the Baker–Venka- taraman rearrangement and cyclization,[5] a 6-endo-dig cycliza- tion of alkyne ketones,[6] a Friedel–Crafts acylation,[7] and cycli- sation of b-diketones[8] among others.[9] Additionally, non- metal-mediated ring-forming processes on simple chro- mones[10] and oxidative alkylation of these ring systems have been reported.[11] (cid:211) 2015 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim In 2013, we described a racemic synthesis of several anthra- pyranones, including BE-26554 A[12] through the cyclisation of a b-ketosulfoxide upon addition of a suitable aldehyde.[13] Given the efficient synthesis of the pyran-4-one core we as- sumed this method could also be applied to a synthesis of her- aclemycin B (3). The anthracene ring system was prepared through a Diels–Alder type cycloaddition of 2-bromo-8-isopro- poxynaphthalene-1,4-dione (5) and 1-methoxy-3-methyl-1-tri- methylsilyoxy-1,3-butadiene (6) (Scheme 1).[14] Further function- al group manipulation afforded the key intermediate b-keto- sulfoxide 7.[13b] Scheme 1. Synthesis of ((cid:156))-heraclemycin B (3) and 2-methyl-1-hexanal (8). TMS = trimethylsilyl.

Through a retrosynthetic disconnection of the natural prod- uct 3, the desired synthon for the addition and annulation pro- cess with compound 7 was the aldehyde 8. The relatively cheap hexanoic acid (9) was used as the starting material for this short synthesis. Treatment of compound 9 with two equiv- alents of lithium diisopropylamine (LDA), followed by alkylation with iodomethane gave a crude mixture containing the a-me- thylated carboxylic acid (Scheme 1).[15] The crude mixture was reduced to the alcohol 10 under standard reaction conditions (lithium aluminium hydride in diethyl ether at 0 8C) in reasona- ble yield over two steps (47 %). Oxidation with Dess-Martin pe- riodinane (DMP) afforded the required aldehyde 8 in 79 % yield.[16] Further purification of this aldehyde proved problem- atic, and thus the aldehyde was further reacted in the crude form. Asian J. Org. Chem. 2015, 4, 936 – 942 The union of the b-ketosulfoxide 7 and the aldehyde 8, through an addition and annulation process, afforded the de- sired compound, tetracycle 11, in 56 % yield. Initially, the for- mation of the 4-pyranone ring system with C2 functionality was spectroscopically confirmed by the existence of a distinct resonance at d = 6.33 ppm (assigned to the C3 4-pyranone ole- finic proton) in the 1H NMR spectrum and later confirmed by a full spectroscopic analysis. Oxidative demethylation of the anthracene B ring of compound 11 with silver(II) oxide in the presence of nitric acid resulted in anthracenone 12 in good yield (68 %).[6b, 13b, 14c, 17] Following this process, the A ring phenol was restored through the deprotection of the isopropoxy ether with boron trichloride, providing the natural product ((cid:156))-heraclemycin B (3) in a quantitative yield.

The 1H and 13C NMR resonances of the two spectra of ((cid:156))-heraclemycin B (3) mirrored those reported in the original isolation paper[4] (for a full table of matched data, please see the supporting information). In each of these spectra six reso- nances in the 13C NMR (d = 39.0, 34.2, 29.6, 22.7, 18.5, and 14.1 ppm) support the presence of the D ring C2 hex-2-yl chain. The single crystal X-ray structure of the natural product 3 confirms the structure. The molecule is shown in Figure 2 with the crystallographic details given in the supporting infor- mation. Figure 2. The X-ray crystal structure of natural product heraclemycin B (3). CCDC 1063934 contains the supplementary crystallographic data for this paper. These data are provided free of charge by The Cambridge Crystallo- graphic Data Centre. Given the annulation process, generating the 4-pyranone ring system was the key step in our synthesis, a small compari- son with other aldehydes was conducted (Table 1). The reac- tion of simple saturated and non-branched aldehydes per- formed well in good yields (entries 1, 3, 5, 7, and 8). The in- creasing carbon chain does not hinder the reaction efficiency in the production of the 4-pyranone ring system. Adorning the aldehyde with a remote electron-withdrawing group in the form of 4,4,4-trifluorobutanal (entry 4) resulted in a slightly lower yield of 65 % when compared with butanal. Recently we have reported this reaction leading to anthracene products in medicinal chemistry studies.[18] Annulations involving alde- (cid:211) 2015 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim hydes bearing a methyl group in the a position were medium to high yielding (entries 2 and 6). The cyclisation was also suc- cessful with an aldehyde bearing remote olefins (entry 9).

A proposed mechanism is described in Scheme 2 through initial formation of sulfenic-acid-type intermediate 21 (or equivalent enolate), which participates in a nucleophilic attack of the aldehyde followed by protonation to intermediate 22. A Scheme 2. Proposed mechanism for b-ketosulfoxide cyclisation of 4-pyra- nones. Asian J. Org. Chem. 2015, 4, 936 – 942 Table 1. Formation of 4-pyranones with various aldehydes. [a] Aldehyde (3 equiv.), piperidine (cat.), toluene, reflux, 2 h; [b] previously reported; [c] Crude aldehyde used [d] 2 equivalents of aldehyde used. similar Knoevenagel type condensation is proposed by the groups of Lee[13e] and Kozlowski[13c] to form intermediate 23. Al- ternatively protonation of the alcohol within 22 followed by cyclisation and the elimination of water could also be responsi- ble for the formation of intermediate 23. The final step in- volves elimination of methane sulfenic acid resulting in the 4- pyranone ring as proposed by others in the literature.[13a, c] In order to explore the possibility of further chemoselective functionalization of ((cid:156))-heraclemycin B (3) we investigated other methods of attaching further functionality at C1’ post an- nulation. Firstly oxidative demethylation of the bismethoxy-an- thracene B ring within compound 17 was completed to give the crude anthraquinone 26. Similar to our previous synthetic efforts, then attempted (Scheme 3).[13b, 18–19] To this end, compound 26 was subjected Scheme 3. Introduction of unsaturation at C1’. DMAP = 4-dimethylaminopyri- dine. to the bispyridinium complex in DMF resulting in olefin 27 in a poor yield of 33 %. Given the poor yield of this final olefina- tion process the pathway could only serve as a potential deri- vatization method for medicinal chemistry studies, however, it is not an effective alternative route to the natural product 3 through hydrogenation.

In summary, we have demonstrated a straightforward ap- proach to the anthrapyran-2-one heraclemycin B (3). This is the first reported total synthesis of this bioactive natural product. Future work with this class of compounds will concentrate on SAR studies specifically at the C2 position potentially from compound 22. The biological effects of such compounds will be investigated at a later date. All reactions were performed under argon and at ambient temper- ature unless stated otherwise. Hexanoic acid and aldehydes used for the annulation were sourced from Lancaster, Alfa Aeser, and Sigma–Aldrich. They we used as re- ceived with the exception of isobutyraldehyde, which was distilled prior to the reaction. High-pressure reactions were carried out in a high-pressure laboratory autoclave reactor Model I containing a 100 mL glass liner from Carl Roth. Special precautions were taken with this apparatus when working with CO due to its high toxicity. The reactor is situated in a fully ventilated room with external purge line to ensure no exposure to the gas. 1H and 13C NMR spec- 1H and tra were acquired on a Varian 400 (399.85 MHz for 100.5 MHz for 13C), Bruker AV500 (500.13 MHz for 1H and 125.8 MHz for 13C), or a Bruker AV600 (600.13 MHz for 1H and 150.9 MHz for 13C) spectrometer at 25 8C. All chemical shifts (d) were referenced to the residual partially undeuterated solvents and reported in parts per million (ppm). 1H and 13C assignments were made with the aid of DEPT, COSY, HSQC, and HMBC spectroscopy where deemed appropriate. Infrared spectra samples were measured di- rectly with an ATR adapter and acquired on a PerkinElmer Spec- trum One spectrometer at 2 cm¢1 resolution. Mass spectra were re- corded on a Waters LCT Premier XE instrument. The reported re- tention factors (Rf) were acquired via TLC performed on Merck silica gel 60 F254 precoated aluminium sheets. Visualization of de- veloped plates was achieved through the use of appropriate stains under a 254 nm or 365 nm UV lamp. Column chromatography was performed using silica gel 60 (0.04–0.063) supplied by Merck, unless otherwise stated. Chromatography solvents were distilled prior to use. Melting points were recorded on a Reichart heated- stage microscope.
